Creating a detailed, complete, and accurate demo project within a single response is challenging due to the many configurations, requirements, and file structures. However, I can provide a simple example that can serve as a basis for you to start configuring the end-to-end functionality.

In this example, we will use Spring Boot version 2.5.6 and Spring Cloud version 2020.0.4. We will have the following services:

1. Eureka server
2. API Gateway
3. Microservice A

Before going into the implementation details, make sure you have JDK 11 or higher installed and an integrated development environment (IDE) such as IntelliJ IDEA or Spring Tool Suite.

1. Initialize and configure the parent Maven project:

- Create a new folder as the base folder for your project.
- Open the folder in your preferred IDE and create a new Maven project.
- Set the packaging type to `pom` in the pom.xml file.
- Add the parent Spring Cloud and project dependencies:

```xml
<dependencyManagement>
    <dependencies>
        <dependency>
            <groupId>org.springframework.cloud</groupId>
            <artifactId>spring-cloud-dependencies</artifactId>
            <version>2020.0.4</version>
            <type>pom</type>
            <scope>import</scope>
        </dependency>
    </dependencies>
</dependencyManagement>

<dependencies>
    <!-- Add common dependencies for your microservices and other modules here -->
</dependencies>
```

2. Configure the Eureka server:

- Create a new Maven Module called `eureka-server` within the parent project.
- Add the following dependencies to the pom.xml file:

```xml
<dependencies>
    <dependency>
        <groupId>org.springframework.cloud</groupId>
        <artifactId>spring-cloud-starter-netflix-eureka-server</artifactId>
    </dependency>
</dependencies>
```

- Create an `EurekaServerApplication` class, and add the `@EnableEurekaServer` and `@SpringBootApplication` annotations to the class:

```java
import org.springframework.boot.SpringApplication;
import org.springframework.boot.autoconfigure.SpringBootApplication;
import org.springframework.cloud.netflix.eureka.server.EnableEurekaServer;

@EnableEurekaServer
@SpringBootApplication
public class EurekaServerApplication {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SpringApplication.run(EurekaServerApplication.class, args);
    }
}
```

- Create an `application.properties` file under the `src/main/resources` folder, and add the following configuration:

```
server.port=8761
spring.application.name=eureka-server
eureka.client.register-with-eureka=false
eureka.client.fetch-registry=false
```

3. Configure the API Gateway:

- Create a new Maven Module called `api-gateway` within the parent project.
- Add the following dependencies to the pom.xml file:

```xml
<dependencies>
    <dependency>
        <groupId>org.springframework.cloud</groupId>
        <artifactId>spring-cloud-starter-gateway</artifactId>
    </dependency>
    <dependency>
        <groupId>org.springframework.cloud</groupId>
        <artifactId>spring-cloud-starter-netflix-eureka-client</artifactId>
    </dependency>
</dependencies>
```

- Create an `ApiGatewayApplication` class, and add the `@SpringBootApplication` annotation to the class:

```java
import org.springframework.boot.SpringApplication;
import org.springframework.boot.autoconfigure.SpringBootApplication;

@SpringBootApplication
public class ApiGatewayApplication {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SpringApplication.run(ApiGatewayApplication.class, args);
    }
}
```

- Create an `application.properties` file under the `src/main/resources` folder, and add the following configuration:

```
server.port=8080
spring.application.name=api-gateway
eureka.client.serviceUrl.defaultZone=http://localhost:8761/eureka
```

- Create a `RouteConfig` class within the `api-gateway` module and define the routes:

```java
import org.springframework.cloud.gateway.route.RouteLocator;
import org.springframework.cloud.gateway.route.builder.RouteLocatorBuilder;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Bean;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Configuration;

@Configuration
public class RouteConfig {

    @Bean
    public RouteLocator routeLocator(RouteLocatorBuilder builder) {
        return builder.routes()
            .route("microservice-a", r -> r.path("/microservice-a/**")
                .uri("lb://microservice-a"))
            .build();
    }
}
```

4. Configure Microservice A:

- Create a new Maven Module called `microservice-a` within the parent project.
- Add the following dependencies to the pom.xml file:

```xml
<dependencies>
    <dependency>
        <groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>
        <artifactId>spring-boot-starter-web</artifactId>
    </dependency>
    <dependency>
        <groupId>org.springframework.cloud</groupId>
        <artifactId>spring-cloud-starter-netflix-eureka-client</artifactId>
    </dependency>
</dependencies>
```

- Create an `MicroserviceAApplication` class, and add the `@SpringBootApplication` and `@EnableDiscoveryClient` annotations to the class:

```java
import org.springframework.boot.SpringApplication;
import org.springframework.boot.autoconfigure.SpringBootApplication;
import org.springframework.cloud.client.discovery.EnableDiscoveryClient;

@EnableDiscoveryClient
@SpringBootApplication
public class MicroserviceAApplication {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SpringApplication.run(MicroserviceAApplication.class, args);
    }
}
```

- Create a REST Controller in `MicroserviceA`:

```java
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.GetMapping;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RequestMapping;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RestController;

@RestController
@RequestMapping("/microservice-a")
public class MicroserviceAController {

    @GetMapping
    public String hello() {
        return "Hello from Microservice A";
    }
}
```

- Create an `application.properties` file under the `src/main/resources` folder, and add the following configuration:

```
server.port=8081
spring.application.name=microservice-a
eureka.client.serviceUrl.defaultZone=http://localhost:8761/eureka
```

5. Run the applications:

- Start the Eureka server by running the `EurekaServerApplication` class.
- Start the API Gateway by running the `ApiGatewayApplication` class.
- Start Microservice A by running the `MicroserviceAApplication` class.

6. Test by sending a request to the API Gateway endpoint:

- Open your browser or use a tool like Postman to send a GET request to `http://localhost:8080/microservice-a/`. You should see the response "Hello from Microservice A".

This basic example sets up a Eureka Server, API Gateway, and one microservice. To add more features like OAuth2, Hystrix, monitoring, and tracing, you can follow the previously provided guidelines to extend the project further. Afterward, study the Spring Boot, Spring Cloud, and component-specific documentation for implementation and configuration details.

To add more features to the example project, follow the extra steps below. We'll add RabbitMQ messaging, OAuth2 security, Hystrix, monitoring, and logging.

1. Configure RabbitMQ messaging for Microservice A:

- Add spring-boot-starter-amqp to your `microservice-a` module pom.xml.

  ```xml
  <dependency>
      <groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>
      <artifactId>spring-boot-starter-amqp</artifactId>
  </dependency>
  ```

- Modify application.properties in `microservice-a` to include RabbitMQ server details (use default Spring Boot properties if you have a local RabbitMQ server running).

  ```
  spring.rabbitmq.host=localhost
  spring.rabbitmq.username=guest
  spring.rabbitmq.password=guest
  ```

- Add a RabbitMQ configuration class to `microservice-a`.

  ```java
  import org.springframework.amqp.core.Binding;
  import org.springframework.amqp.core.BindingBuilder;
  import org.springframework.amqp.core.Queue;
  import org.springframework.amqp.core.TopicExchange;
  import org.springframework.context.annotation.Bean;
  import org.springframework.context.annotation.Configuration;

  @Configuration
  public class RabbitMqConfig {

      public static final String QUEUE_NAME = "test-queue";
      public static final String EXCHANGE_NAME = "test-exchange";
      public static final String ROUTING_KEY = "test-routing-key";

      @Bean
      public Queue queue() {
          return new Queue(QUEUE_NAME, false);
      }

      @Bean
      public TopicExchange exchange() {
          return new TopicExchange(EXCHANGE_NAME);
      }

      @Bean
      public Binding binding(Queue queue, TopicExchange exchange) {
          return BindingBuilder.bind(queue).to(exchange).with(ROUTING_KEY);
      }
  }
  ```

- Add message producer and consumer classes to `microservice-a`.

  ```java
  import org.springframework.amqp.rabbit.annotation.RabbitListener;
  import org.springframework.amqp.rabbit.core.RabbitTemplate;
  import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Autowired;
  import org.springframework.stereotype.Component;
  import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.GetMapping;
  import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RequestMapping;
  import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RestController;

  @Component
  public class MessageProducer {
      @Autowired
      private RabbitTemplate rabbitTemplate;

      public void sendMessage(String message) {
          rabbitTemplate.convertAndSend(RabbitMqConfig.EXCHANGE_NAME, RabbitMqConfig.ROUTING_KEY, message);
      }
  }

  @Component
  public class MessageConsumer {
      @RabbitListener(queues = RabbitMqConfig.QUEUE_NAME)
      public void receiveMessage(String message) {
          System.out.println("Received message: " + message);
      }
  }

  @RestController
  @RequestMapping("/messaging")
  public class MessagingController {
      @Autowired
      private MessageProducer messageProducer;

      @GetMapping
      public String sendMessage() {
          messageProducer.sendMessage("Hello from Microservice A!");
          return "Message sent!";
      }
  }
  ```

Continuing from the previous response, we will now add OAuth2 security with a separate authorization server, configure Hystrix for fault tolerance, and set up monitoring and logging with Zipkin and Sleuth.

2. Configure OAuth2 security:

- Create a new Maven module called `auth-server` in the parent project.
- Add the following dependencies to the `pom.xml` file:

```xml
<dependencies>
    <dependency>
        <groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>
        <artifactId>spring-boot-starter-security</artifactId>
    </dependency>
    <dependency>
        <groupId>org.springframework.security.oauth.boot</groupId>
        <artifactId>spring-security-oauth2-autoconfigure</artifactId>
    </dependency>
</dependencies>
```

- Create a new `AuthServerApplication` class, and add the `@SpringBootApplication` annotation to the class:

```java
import org.springframework.boot.SpringApplication;
import org.springframework.boot.autoconfigure.SpringBootApplication;

@SpringBootApplication
public class AuthServerApplication {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SpringApplication.run(AuthServerApplication.class, args);
    }
}
```

- Create an `AuthorizationServerConfiguration` class to configure the authorization server:

```java
import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Autowired;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Configuration;
import org.springframework.security.crypto.password.PasswordEncoder;
import org.springframework.security.oauth2.config.annotation.configurers.ClientDetailsServiceConfigurer;
import org.springframework.security.oauth2.config.annotation.web.configuration.AuthorizationServerConfigurerAdapter;
import org.springframework.security.oauth2.config.annotation.web.configuration.EnableAuthorizationServer;
import org.springframework.security.oauth2.config.annotation.web.configurers.AuthorizationServerEndpointsConfigurer;
import org.springframework.security.oauth2.config.annotation.web.configurers.AuthorizationServerSecurityConfigurer;
import org.springframework.security.oauth2.provider.token.TokenStore;
import org.springframework.security.oauth2.provider.token.store.InMemoryTokenStore;

@Configuration
@EnableAuthorizationServer
public class AuthorizationServerConfiguration extends AuthorizationServerConfigurerAdapter {

    @Autowired
    private PasswordEncoder passwordEncoder;

    @Bean
    public TokenStore tokenStore() {
        return new InMemoryTokenStore();
    }

    @Override
    public void configure(ClientDetailsServiceConfigurer clients) throws Exception {
        clients.inMemory()
                .withClient("client")
                .secret(passwordEncoder.encode("client-secret"))
                .authorizedGrantTypes("authorization_code", "refresh_token")
                .scopes("read", "write")
                .autoApprove(true)
                .accessTokenValiditySeconds(86400);
    }

    @Override
    public void configure(AuthorizationServerEndpointsConfigurer endpoints) {
        endpoints.tokenStore(tokenStore());
    }

    @Override
    public void configure(AuthorizationServerSecurityConfigurer oauthServer) {
        oauthServer.tokenKeyAccess("permitAll()")
                .checkTokenAccess("isAuthenticated()");
    }
}
```

- Add OAuth2 and Spring Security configurations to the microservices and API Gateway:

  - Add the required dependencies (spring-boot-starter-security, spring-security-oauth2-autoconfigure) to every module that will be secured (API Gateway and microservices).

  - Add security configurations to secure the services and define the Resource Server and Authentication Manager configurations.

  - Configure the API Gateway to "forward" the access token from incoming requests to backend services. This will allow backend services to verify the access token.

3. Configure Hystrix for fault tolerance:

- Add spring-cloud-starter-netflix-hystrix to your `microservice-a` module dependencies.

  ```xml
  <dependency>
      <groupId>org.springframework.cloud</groupId>
      <artifactId>spring-cloud-starter-netflix-hystrix</artifactId>
  </dependency>
  ```

- Add @EnableCircuitBreaker to `MicroserviceAApplication` class.

- Add @HystrixCommand(fallbackMethod = "fallbackMethodName") to any methods you'd like to protect with a circuit breaker, supplying the name of the fallback method that will be invoked if an error or timeout occurs.

4. Set up monitoring and logging with Zipkin and Sleuth:

- Add spring-cloud-starter-zipkin and spring-cloud-starter-sleuth to every module that you want to monitor and trace (API Gateway and microservices).

  ```xml
  <dependency>
      <groupId>org.springframework.cloud</groupId>
  <artifactId>spring-cloud-starter-zipkin</artifactId>
  </dependency>
  <dependency>
      <groupId>org.springframework.cloud</groupId>
  <artifactId>spring-cloud-starter-sleuth</artifactId>
  </dependency>
  ```

- Configure Zipkin URL and sampling rate in the applications properties of each module:

  ```
  spring.zipkin.base-url=http://localhost:9411
  spring.sleuth.sampler.probability=1.0
  ```

- Run a local instance of Zipkin for testing purposes using Docker:

  ```
  docker run -d -p 9411:9411 openzipkin/zipkin
  ```

After setting up these additional features, consult the component-specific documentation for further configuration details and best practices. This will help improve the functionality, security, and reliability of your application.

To implement OAuth2 and Spring Security in the API Gateway and Microservice A, follow the steps below:

1. Add required dependencies to API Gateway and Microservice A:

- Open the 'pom.xml' file for both `api-gateway` and `microservice-a` modules.
- Add spring-boot-starter-security and spring-security-oauth2-autoconfigure.

```xml
<dependency>
    <groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>
    <artifactId>spring-boot-starter-security</artifactId>
</dependency>
<dependency>
    <groupId>org.springframework.security.oauth.boot</groupId>
    <artifactId>spring-security-oauth2-autoconfigure</artifactId>
</dependency>
```

2. Configure Resource Server for Microservice A:

- Create a new configuration class `ResourceServerConfig` in `microservice-a`.
- Add @EnableResourceServer and @EnableWebSecurity annotations to the class.

```java
import org.springframework.boot.autoconfigure.security.SecurityProperties;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Configuration;
import org.springframework.core.annotation.Order;
import org.springframework.security.config.annotation.web.builders.HttpSecurity;
import org.springframework.security.config.annotation.web.configuration.EnableWebSecurity;
import org.springframework.security.oauth2.config.annotation.web.configuration.EnableResourceServer;
import org.springframework.security.oauth2.config.annotation.web.configuration.ResourceServerConfigurerAdapter;
import org.springframework.security.oauth2.provider.error.OAuth2AccessDeniedHandler;

@Configuration
@EnableResourceServer
@EnableWebSecurity
@Order(SecurityProperties.BASIC_AUTH_ORDER)
public class ResourceServerConfig extends ResourceServerConfigurerAdapter {

    @Override
    public void configure(HttpSecurity http) throws Exception {
        http
            .csrf().disable()
            .authorizeRequests()
            .anyRequest().authenticated()
            .and()
            .exceptionHandling().accessDeniedHandler(new OAuth2AccessDeniedHandler());
    }
}
```

3. Configure API Gateway to secure gateway routes and forward OAuth2 access tokens:

- Create a new configuration class `SecurityConfig` in the `api-gateway` module.

```java
import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Value;
import org.springframework.cloud.gateway.config.GlobalCorsProperties;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Bean;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Configuration;
import org.springframework.http.HttpMethod;
import org.springframework.security.config.annotation.web.builders.HttpSecurity;
import org.springframework.security.config.annotation.web.configuration.EnableWebSecurity;
import org.springframework.security.config.annotation.web.configuration.WebSecurityConfigurerAdapter;
import org.springframework.security.oauth2.client.AuthorizedClientRepository;
import org.springframework.security.oauth2.client.InMemoryOAuth2AuthorizedClientService;
import org.springframework.security.oauth2.client.OAuth2AuthorizedClientService;
import org.springframework.security.oauth2.client.registration.ClientRegistrationRepository;
import org.springframework.security.oauth2.client.registration.InMemoryClientRegistrationRepository;
import org.springframework.security.oauth2.client.web.AuthenticatedPrincipalOAuth2AuthorizedClientRepository;
import org.springframework.security.oauth2.client.web.reactive.function.client.ServletOAuth2AuthorizedClientExchangeFilterFunction;
import org.springframework.security.oauth2.core.AuthorizationGrantType;
import org.springframework.security.oauth2.core.ClientAuthenticationMethod;
import org.springframework.security.oauth2.jwt.JwtDecoders;
import org.springframework.web.reactive.function.client.WebClient;

@Configuration
@EnableWebSecurity
public class SecurityConfig extends WebSecurityConfigurerAdapter {

    @Value("${auth-server-base-url}")
    private String authServerBaseUrl;

    @Override
    protected void configure(HttpSecurity http) throws Exception {
        http
            .csrf().disable()
            .authorizeRequests()
            .mvcMatchers(HttpMethod.GET, "/microservice-a/**").authenticated()
            .and()
            .oauth2Login()
            .and()
            .oauth2ResourceServer().jwt()
            .jwtAuthenticationConverter(new JwtAuthConverter())
            .decoder(JwtDecoders.fromIssuerLocation(authServerBaseUrl));
    }

    @Bean
    public WebClient.Builder webClientBuilder(ClientRegistrationRepository clients,
                                              OAuth2AuthorizedClientService auth2AuthorizedClientService) {
        ServletOAuth2AuthorizedClientExchangeFilterFunction oauth2Function = new ServletOAuth2AuthorizedClientExchangeFilterFunction(clients, auth2AuthorizedClientService);
        return WebClient.builder().apply(oauth2Function.oauth2Configuration());
    }

    @Bean
    public ClientRegistrationRepository clientRegistrationRepository(@Value("${client-id}") String clientId,
                                                                     @Value("${client-secret}") String clientSecret) {
        return new InMemoryClientRegistrationRepository(
            clientRegistration(clientId, clientSecret)
        );
    }

    @Bean
    public OAuth2AuthorizedClientService oauth2AuthorizedClientService(ClientRegistrationRepository clients) {
        return new InMemoryOAuth2AuthorizedClientService(clients);
    }

    @Bean
    public AuthorizedClientRepository authorizedClientRepository(OAuth2AuthorizedClientService auth2AuthorizedClientService) {
        return new AuthenticatedPrincipalOAuth2AuthorizedClientRepository(auth2AuthorizedClientService);
    }

    private ClientRegistration clientRegistration(String clientId, String clientSecret) {
        return ClientRegistration.withRegistrationId("client")
            .clientId(clientId)
            .clientSecret(clientSecret)
            .clientAuthenticationMethod(ClientAuthenticationMethod.BASIC)
            .authorizationGrantType(AuthorizationGrantType.AUTHORIZATION_CODE)
            .redirectUri("http://localhost:8080/login/oauth2/code/client")
            .scope("user_info")
            .authorizationUri(authServerBaseUrl + "/oauth/authorize")
            .tokenUri(authServerBaseUrl + "/oauth/token")
            .userInfoUri(authServerBaseUrl + "/user/me")
            .userNameAttributeName("id")
            .build();
  }
}
```

- Make sure to configure the "authServerBaseUrl", "client-id", and "client-secret" properties in the `application.properties` of the `api-gateway` module.

4. Run the applications:

- Start the auth server by running the `AuthServerApplication` class.
- Restart the API Gateway (`ApiGatewayApplication` class) and Microservice A (`MicroserviceAApplication` class).

5. Test the secure API by sending a request to the API Gateway endpoint:

- Open your browser or use a tool like Postman to send an authorized GET request to `http://localhost:8080/microservice-a/`. You should see the response "Hello from Microservice A".

By following these steps, you have now added OAuth2 security to your API Gateway and Microservice A. The API Gateway authenticates requests using OAuth2 tokens and forwards them to the microservices. The microservices check the token for authorization before processing the request.
